❓-faq chat

    Use the up and down arrow keys to navigate between messages quickly. New messages will be added to the bottom of the list as they come in.

    Welcome to #❓-faq!

    This is the start of the #❓-faq channel.
    March 10, 2024

  1. ŁW — 03/10/2024 5:16 PM

    How to start? How do I use the Discord bot?

    There are multiple commands you can use with the CTF bot. They can be put on any channel you can write on (the result will be displayed just for you), but to avoid accidentally spilling the flag on the public chat we suggest to talk to the bot directly @1753CTF Available commands are: /create_team <name> - allowing to create a new team /team_code - showing your team's secret code that you can share with your collegues /join_team <code> - allowing others to join your team /team_info - showing basic info about your team /team_info <other_team_name> - showing basic info about other team and the most important one: /submit_flag <flag> - allowing to submit flags and get ranking points And by the way, the flag format is 1753c{...} Thanks to @bart for pointing out discrepancies in command names. Now they're okay. (edited)
  2. [5:20 PM]

    How to get help?

    There is a dedicated ⁠🙋-support channel you can use to create a ticket to our support. It will create a separate channel for you that you can use to communicate with organizers team Feel free to ask any questions you might have, especially if you are a beginner player. We will do our best to support you, but our team won't give out any hints on how to solve particular challenges. You need to try harder! We will do our best to support the event through it's entire length, but between 1:00 AM UTC and 7:00 AM UTC we might not be available getting some sleap. Thanks for understanding! (edited)

  3. ŁW — 03/10/2024 5:33 PM

    What will be the challenges?

    We've prepared over 20 challenges in different categories including:
    • WEB - challenges requiring to exploit web application vulnerabilities
    • REV - challenges requiring analysis and disassembly of compiled binaries
    • CRYPTO - challenges requiring the understanding of cryptographic algorithms
    • PWN - challenges requiring the exploitation of memory-related vulnerabilities
    • OSINT - challenges requiring gathering information from public sources
    • STEGANO - challenges requiring finding messages hidden in audio/video files
    • MISC - other challenges that did not fit in any of the categories above
    Vast majority of the challenges will be available right from the start of the game. At 7:00AM UTC on Saturday we're gonna publish a second round of tasks. Some of the tasks in the second round will be a continuation of the first round challenges. Before the start we publish a few test challenges, so you can play with our Discord bot and get familiar with the infrastructure. These challenges will be removed before the event start. All challenges will be published on ⁠🔥-tasks channel (edited)
  4. [5:34 PM]

    How the ranking works?

    Every team gets points for each flag submitted. The number of points is equal to the flag's current value which is calculated as follows:
    Points per challenge = MAX(500 - number_of_solves * 10, 100)
    So each solve of a challenge decreases its value by 10 points so easier challenges will have less value than more demanding ones. The maximum points per challenge is 500, the least is 100. In case multiple teams got the same number of points, the team who sent their last flag earlier will be above the team that got the flag later. You can monitor ⁠🏆-ranking channel to see how your team is doing. (edited)

  5. ŁW — 03/10/2024 8:57 PM

    How to find a team?

    Capture The Flags are best when experienced in a team. Sharing knowledge, looking how others solve certain challenges, learning from each other - that is the bread and butter of CTFs. Don't have a team yet? No worries. There is a dedicated ⁠looking-for-team channel that you can use to find others who are searching for the company. (edited)

  6. ŁW — 03/10/2024 9:23 PM

    Will there be official write-ups?

    CTF write-ups are detailed solutions or explanations about how challenges were solved. These write-ups often include the methodologies, tools, codes, and thought processes used by the participants to solve cybersecurity puzzles or challenges during the competition. They serve as educational resources for others to learn from and improve their own cybersecurity skills. We want to give you a moment to shine so there will be a dedicated channel to share your solutions with others and discuss them. We're gonna open it right after the CTF end. On the other hand we don't want to leave you hanging, so not later than 1 hour after the event's finish we're gonna publish official writeups from challenge authors. (edited)

  7. ŁW — 03/10/2024 9:45 PM

    Will this be ranked on CTFtime?

    CTFtime provides rankings of teams based on their performance in various Capture The Flag competitions. Teams earn points based on their results in these competitions, and CTFtime aggregates these points to create global rankings. These rankings allow teams to see how they compare to others in the cybersecurity community worldwide, offering a competitive and motivational aspect to participating in CTFs. Our CTF scores will be submitted to CTFtime right after the event's end, so your team can gain ranking point in there! You can also visit our page on CTFtime and click "I will participate" to let others know you are interested in this event https://ctftime.org/event/2234 (edited)
    8. March 13, 2024

  8. ŁW — 03/13/2024 4:52 AM

    Is there a limit on the team size?

    No. We do not limit team size as on an online event there is no way to enforce it. When talking with our sponsors we figured the team size would be around 5 people so each of the prizes comes multiplied by five, but that is just an assumption. If your team is bigger, that is totally fine. The only downside is that you might have trouble deciding how to share the prize you're gonna win (edited)
